comments.text:
Thanks, Ddogbert! &Acirc;&nbsp;I wish I knew anything about the Cube software and maybe I could help. &Acirc;&nbsp;You could always try deleting the top polygons in Blender and see what your printer's slicing software thinks of it. &Acirc;&nbsp;I've heard that Cura will print such meshes, but Slic3r considers the open top a "hole" and wants it closed. &Acirc;&nbsp;<br />
Printing this way is really kind of a round about way of doing something that seems like it should be easy in modeling software, but isn't. &Acirc;&nbsp;<br />
Can you print with Gcode sliced in a different program on the Cube? &Acirc;&nbsp;Seems like you could slice in Slic3r and bring the Gcode into your print software to feed it to the printer. &Acirc;&nbsp;

Wow, thanks for the link and thanks for all the hard work on your testing. &Acirc;&nbsp;<br />
0.9.7 was a major improvement, but I still find myself reverting to 0.8.4 because of the way 0.9.7 handles small details. &Acirc;&nbsp;Went from not filling most small gaps that should have been, to filling ALL small gaps even if there's 0% infill.<br />
Still need to try KISSlicer. &Acirc;&nbsp; &Acirc;&nbsp;

